# Callback Hell

Suppose your application performs these tasks in sequence:

```
Login

↓

Get User

↓

Get Orders

↓

Make Payment

↓

Send Email
```

Using callbacks, the code becomes:

```javascript
login(function(user) {

    getOrders(user, function(order) {

        makePayment(order, function(payment) {

            sendEmail(payment, function() {

                console.log("Done");

            });

        });

    });

});
```

Notice how every callback is nested inside another.

```
login(
    getOrders(
        makePayment(
            sendEmail()
        )
    )
)
```

This deeply nested structure is called **Callback Hell** (also known as the **Pyramid of Doom**).

## Problems with Callback Hell

- Difficult to read
- Difficult to debug
- Error handling becomes complicated
- Hard to maintain
- Difficult to scale

